05112nam a22007215i 9781501717499DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20181995nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017174997 a10.7591/97815017174992doi  a(DE-B1597)503291  a(OCoLC)1038496339  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD1417.T66 1995 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a338.1/09172/41 aTomich, Thomas P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTransforming Agrarian Economies :bOpportunities Seized, Opportunities Missed /cPeter Kilby, Thomas P. Tomich, Bruce F. Johnston. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (496 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF BOXES -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPart 1: The Rural Economy in the Development Process -- tCHAPTER ONE. POVERTY AND THE RURAL ECONOMY -- tCHAPTER TWO. STRUCTURAL TRANSFORMATION -- tCHAPTER THREE. JAPAN, THE UNITED STATES, AND STRUCTURAL TRANSFORMATION -- tPART TWO: FROM STRUCTURE TO STRATEGY -- tCHAPTER FOUR. SMALL FARMS IN A BROAD-BASED AGRICULTURAL STRATEGY -- tCHAPTER FIVE. AGRICULTURAL STRATEGIES AND AGRARIAN STRUCTURE -- tCHAPTER SIX. LINKS BETWEEN AGRICULTURE AND INDUSTRY -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. FERTILIZER PRODUCTION: STRATEGIC PITFALL? -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. FISCAL BALANCE AND SOCIAL PROGRAM PRIORITIES -- tPART THREE: CHOICES AND CONSEQUENCES -- tCHAPTER NINE. CHINA AND THE SOVIET UNION -- tCHAPTER TEN. TAIWAN AND MEXICO -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN. KENYA AND TANZANIA -- tCHAPTER TWELVE. GETTING PRIORITIES RIGHT -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX OF NAMES -- tINDEX OF SUBJECTS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world's 58 poorest countries are diverse in many respects, but they share the characteristic of a labor force overwhelmingly dependent on agriculture. Challenging the assumption that mass poverty and chronic hunger are insoluble problems, this book systematically explores the multiple aspects of economic development in these countries, which are home to 60 percent of the world's population.The authors offer a broad-based development strategy to raise incomes through agricultural productivity growth and expanded rural employment. They present rich new information on the rural informal sector and on agriculture-industry interactions, and they analyze the impact of macroeconomic and social policies on the rural economy. Policy instruments aimed at bringing about broad-based development are carefully assessed from fiscal policy to development of hew seeds and farm implements.The book includes detailed case studies of countries that have seized—or missed—development opportunities. Comparison of the successful economic transformations of Japan and the United States shows how key ideas, which the authors call strategic notions, have enabled policymakers to act with foresight. Analyses of strategic choices in China, the Soviet Union, Taiwan, Mexico, Kenya, and Tanzania also show how development strategies that emerge from the real-world political economy reflect a mix of individual interests and strategic notions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aAgriculture. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aJohnston, Bruce F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKilby, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171749940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97815017